PROMPT: Prompt: Allow for direct interaction with Pat Patterson. "Pat, what are your thoughts on the strengths and weaknesses of Bob Backlund and Afa during this period? Where is the ceiling and floor for each in the context of the promotion and the industry in 1981? Is there a way they could have been used more effectively in the WWWF circa the 1981 time frame? Is there someone from outside the territory from 1981 that may have worked well with either talent?

----

  Direct Interaction with Pat Patterson (1981 Context)    

 Pat Patterson adjusts his chair, leans forward, and responds with his characteristic blend of insight and practicality.   

---

  On Bob Backlund  :  
"Bob is a workhorse, no question about it. The man’s conditioning is off the charts—he can go an hour without breaking a sweat, which makes him perfect for the WWWF’s style of long matches. His technical skills are superb, and the Crossface Chicken Wing is a legitimate threat that fans buy into.  

The strength of Bob is also his weakness. He’s almost too squeaky clean. He doesn’t have that edge or fire that hooks the more casual fans who thrive on charisma. His promos are straightforward, which fits his persona but limits his ability to adapt to bigger, more colorful personalities. In 1981, he’s holding down the fort as champion, but his ceiling is tied to whether the WWWF audience continues to value technical wrestling over the larger-than-life characters."  

  On Afa  :  
"Afa is a wild card, and that’s his biggest strength. He’s believable—when he no-sells those headshots or throws his Samoan Drop, you believe every bit of it. Pairing him with Sika as the Wild Samoans was brilliant because they have an aura of danger.  

As a singles guy, Afa is tougher to place. He’s not the most technically gifted, and his matches can slow down too much if he doesn’t have the right dance partner. His ceiling is solid as a heel—he could headline C- and B-shows easily, but his style might struggle against top-tier faces like Bruno or Pedro Morales in longer main events. Used right, though, he’s the kind of guy who makes champions look better. His floor? He risks being stuck as ‘just a tag guy’ if we don’t give him enough opportunities to shine on his own."  

---

  On Their Use in the WWWF (1981)  :  
"Bob is where he should be as champion, but there’s room to freshen things up. He’s doing a lot of the same kind of matches, and fans are starting to expect the formula. If we gave him an edgier opponent—someone with big personality or a controversial edge—it would force Bob to adapt and could elevate both guys. Maybe push him harder in terms of stipulations, like a No DQ or Texas Death Match—something to shake things up.  

For Afa, we could lean into his singles potential more. Give him a short feud with Bob on the B- and C-shows to show the crowd he’s a credible threat. Let him win a few matches in dominating fashion—maybe even against a mid-tier face like Dominic DeNucci—to build momentum."  

---

  On Outside Talent from 1981  :  
"If we’re looking outside the WWWF, I think someone like Dusty Rhodes would be perfect against Bob. Dusty’s charisma and energy would be a complete contrast to Bob’s straight-laced, technical style. Dusty could cut promos that force Bob to step out of his comfort zone.  

For Afa, you’d want someone who could keep up with his power but also bring speed and excitement. A guy like Tommy Rich from Georgia Championship Wrestling could work. Tommy had that babyface fire and could sell like crazy for Afa’s offense, making Afa look even more dangerous."  

---

  Closing Thoughts  :  
"Both Bob and Afa are assets to the WWWF, but they need the right environments to shine. For Bob, it’s about giving him compelling opponents who challenge his character. For Afa, it’s about showcasing his wildness in matches where his strengths—intensity and raw power—are on full display. The key is finding those balance points and using them to elevate not just these guys, but the whole card."  

 Pat pauses, then smirks slightly.  "But hey, in this business, even the best plans can change once you’re out there in front of the crowd. That’s why we always stay ready to adapt."  

